explanation:
For each symbol below I state why its definition/implementation is required to determine compliance with the MISRA for-loop rule for OS_ModuleUnload. The rule requires inspecting any for-loops in the function and in any functions called from its body (loops inside those callees count as part of the body). You must examine implementations, types, macros and globals to see if any for-loops exist and whether their clauses use or modify objects that are modified in the loop body.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Called at the top of OS_ModuleUnload; its implementation must be inspected for any for-loops (and their loop counters/side effects) because behavior of called functions is part of a for-loop body.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to inspect nested loops or use of shared objects/indices that might violate the clause constraints.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; may contain loops or index arithmetic that act as loop counters or modify objects used elsewhere.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; its implementation might modify token/index objects or contain loops needing analysis.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to check for loops or side effects relevant to the transaction/token objects.
- OS_ModuleUnload_Impl: Conditionally called from OS_ModuleUnload; must be inspected for internal for-loops and for use/modification of any objects that would violate the rule when considered part of the caller's for-loop body.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Used by OS_ModuleUnload_Impl (and referenced by the static graph); its body may contain loops or index modifications affecting loop-counter/side-effect analysis.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: Called at end of OS_ModuleUnload; its implementation (and any loops inside) is required to ensure no for-loop misuse occurs in the overall operation.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish: Callee of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete; include to inspect nested loops and effects on shared objects/tokens.
- OS_NotifyEvent: Callee of OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete; include because it might perform iterations/events that modify objects used as loop counters elsewhere.
- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET (macro): Macro used to read OS_module_table with token; macro expansion may include indexing logic or calls to OS_ObjectIndexFromToken or other constructs that contain loops or persistent side effects.
- OS_module_table (global): The table accessed by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its structure/layout may reveal whether indexing uses side-effecting accesses or whether accesses modify objects referenced in loops.
- OS_module_internal_record_t (type): The structure of 'module' is needed to know the fields accessed (module_type) and whether other fields are manipulated in called functions or loops.
- OS_MODULE_TYPE_DYNAMIC (constant): Value compared against module->module_type controls conditional call to OS_ModuleUnload_Impl; include to understand control flow and whether different code paths introduce loops.
- OS_object_token_t (type): Type of the 'token' passed between functions; implementations may treat this as an index or structure and modify it, which affects whether a for-loop counter is modified in call chains.
- OS_SUCCESS (constant): Return value compared after OS_ObjectIdGetById; included to fully understand control flow and whether alternate paths (with loops) are reachable.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE (constant): Parameter to OS_ObjectIdGetById; included to understand the behavior of that call (locking code paths may contain loops) and which implementation paths to inspect.
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE (constant): Parameter to OS_ObjectIdGetById; may select code paths inside OS_ObjectIdGetById that contain loops or modify different objects.

Note: I omitted the UT_* test-stub symbols (unit test harness) because they are typically test stubs; include them only if the build under analysis links those stubs into the production call chain. The listed symbols are the minimal set needed to inspect all relevant called implementations, macros and data structures that could contain for-loops or modify objects used as loop counters, per the MISRA rule definition.
